introduction.p:
Recall too the definition of a negative or zero exponent:
Definition of Negative and Zero Exponents


        \begin{aligned}
        a^{-n} \amp = \frac{1}{a^n} \amp\amp (a \ne 0) \\
        a^0 \amp = 1  \amp\amp (a \ne 0)
        \end{aligned}

example.p:
\begin{align*}
    \text{a}\amp. ~x^3\cdot x^{-5} = x^{3-5} = x^{-2} 
    \amp\amp     \text{Apply the first law: Add exponents.} \\
    \text{b}\amp. ~\frac{8x^{-2}}{4x^{-6}}= \frac{8}{4}x^{-2-(-6)} = 2x^4
    \amp\amp     \text{Apply the second law: Subtract exponents.} \\
    \text{c}\amp. ~\left(5x^{-3}\right)^{-2}= 5^{-2}(x^{-3})^{-2}=\frac{x^6}{25}
    \amp\amp     \text{Apply laws IV and III.}
\end{align*}

statement.p:
    Simplify by applying the laws of exponents.



\left(2a^{-4}\right) \left(-4a^2\right)


\dfrac{(r^2)^{-3}}{3r^{-4}}

warning.p:
The laws of exponents do not apply to sums or differences of powers. We can add or subtract like terms, that is, powers of the same variable with the same exponent. For example,
6x^{-2} + 3x^{-2} = 9x^{-2}
but we cannot add or subtract terms with different exponents. Thus, for example,
\begin{align*}
4x^2 \amp- 3x^{-2} \amp\amp \text{cannot be simplified, and}\\
x^{-1} \amp + x^{-3}\amp\amp \text{cannot be simplified}.
\end{align*}

statement.p:
            Which of the following are power functions?



f (x) = \dfrac{1}{3}x^4 + 2


g(x) = \dfrac{1}{3x^4}


h(x) = \dfrac{x + 6}{x^3}

        Write each function as a power function in the form y = kx ^p.



f (x) = {12}{x^2}


g(x) = \dfrac{1}{4x}


h(x) = \dfrac{2}{5x^6}

subsection.p:
Let  k\gt0  be a positive integer, then:







              For all such  k\gt 0 , the graph of
               y=x^{2k-1}
              is shown to the right. The long run behavior of such a function is given by
              \begin{align*}
              x^{2k-1}\to -\infty\ \amp \text{as}\ x\to -\infty\ ,\ \ \text{and}\\
              x^{2k-1}\to \infty\ \amp \text{as}\ x\to \infty.
          \end{align*}
          Examples of such functions are  x,x^3,x^5, etc.

          graphs positive odd powers








                For all such  k\gt 0 , the graph of
                 y=x^{2k}
                is shown to the right. The long run behavior of such a function is given by
                \begin{align*}
                x^{2k}\to \infty\ \amp \text{as}\ x\to \pm\infty.
                \end{align*}
                Examples of such functions are  x^2,x^4,x^6, etc.

            graphs positive even powers








                For all such  k\gt 0 , the graph of
                 y=x^{-(2k-1)}
                is shown to the right. The long run behavior of such a function is given by
                \begin{align*}
                    x^{-(2k-1)}\to 0\ \amp \text{as}\ x\to \pm\infty.
                    \end{align*}
                Examples of such functions are  x^{-1},x^{-3},x^{-5}, etc.

            graphs negative odd powers








                For all such  k\gt 0 , the graph of
                 y=x^{-2k}
                is shown to the right. The long run behavior of such a function is given by
                \begin{align*}
                    x^{-2k}\to 0\ \amp \text{as}\ x\to \pm\infty
                    \end{align*}
                Examples of such functions are  x^{-2},x^{-4},x^{-6}, etc.

            graphs negative even powers
